Super Cook:<br><br>
Christian perspectives on PTSD and mental health are priceless... often they contain the ingredient of spirituality, too frequently overlooked in the secular laboratory.  Those, too blindly addicted to empirical truth, find that they cannot scientifically prove God so therefore they throw him out of the process.  A word of caution... we must understand that religions often carry and convey the pseudo wisdom of man with God's label stamped on it.  We purvey a lot of baloney in the name of God.  I greatly appreciate your views.. as others...and mine, once they are filtered by truth. <br><br>
Trying to train your cat to fetch your slippers, is a wonderful example of forced idealism...because realism simply will not let it occur.  Let us not contaminate our search by seeking to validate our positions with &quot;what we want to believe.&quot;<br><br>
Regarding your observation that Marines seem to have a lower and less severe incident of PTSD raises a red flag in my tower of observation.  I am not a Marine.  I do not need to immortalize the Corps in order to deny my wounds.  If I were a Marine, it is likely that I would focus upon this institution of illustrious standing, realizing that I was a part of it...and possibly slip into that defense mechanism called &quot;identification.&quot;  It is another form of denial.. So well demonstrated by cocky pilots...tough grunts... paratroopers... heroic medics... cannon cockers...Seals... Green Berets...and those who subscribe to a &quot;special bunch.&quot;  Marines ARE a special bunch.  Two sides of an argument seem to appear... &quot;Marines are super tough, therefore are not cry babies.... or Marines see a lot of bad road, uphill, in the rain and are more likely to be traumatized.&quot;  Both are viable arguments... &quot;What is it that the person wants to believe?&quot;  NOTE: Only helicopter pilots experience no pain... and consequently show no weakness.  The only exception is national guard company clerks (providing they are Comanche/Lakota) &lt;BG&gt;<br><br>
Chet did hit the nail on the head... &quot;I learned, for me, that it had nothing to do with me what I did in country&quot; (a little bit of truth) &quot;it was how I internalized it.&quot; (A whole lot more truth.)  The &quot;welcome home&quot; vs. Condemnation you mentioned is... acceptance (pleasure which we seek) vs. Rejection (the greatest pain, which we seek to avoid).  We blindly grope for &quot;control levers&quot; to regain control which = security which = absence of fear = being okay.<br><br>
Cookie, I shared the podium with an active duty Master Gunnery Sergeant yesterday at the Moving Wall (ex-recon in RVN).  He was the epitome of dignity (and something sacred to identify with).  I was taken back by his departure from decorum when he gave me a big boyish hug.  All I did was ask him if he knew you... and welcome him home.  It didn't take him long to become a Jarhead again.  He turned to the Brigadier General, siting next to me and said, &quot;Sir, request permission to break tradition and remove my cover.&quot;  He gave his moving speech with his cover resting beside the microphones.  I gave him a copy of my book and he looked at me as if I was almost good enough to be a Marine.<br><br>
Please join me on the new PTSD thread.<br><br>
MTF<br><br>
P.S.  I lied about how special you are to me...I figured he and the Corps needed a pump.
